Auto-generation of a code snippet with an enum nested in a generic class adds the identifier of the class we're in as superfluous qualifier.

Sample code:

```
namespace DemoCodeAnalyzerOnNestedEnum
{
    internal class DemoClassWithNestedEnum
    {
        public enum DemoNestedEnum
        {
            First,
            Second
        }

        public static string DemoNestedEnumUsage()
        {
            var demoNestedEnumValue = ((new Random()).Next(2) == 0) ? DemoNestedEnum.First : DemoNestedEnum.Second;

            switch
        }
    }
}
```
Put the cursor immediately behind the keyword "switch", press [Tab], replace the selected "switch_on" by "demoNestedEnumValue", and press "Enter". 

Observed result (switch block only):

```
            switch (demoNestedEnumValue)
            {
                case DemoClassWithNestedEnum.DemoNestedEnum.First:
                    break;
                case DemoClassWithNestedEnum.DemoNestedEnum.Second:
                    break;
                default:
                    break;
            }
```
Expected result (switch block only):

```
            switch (demoNestedEnumValue)
            {
                case DemoNestedEnum.First:
                    break;
                case DemoNestedEnum.Second:
                    break;
                default:
                    break;
            }
```

With a non-generic class, the code generation runs just fine.

Not only the code generator, but also the code analyzer has a flaw here: it doesn't issue a message "Simplify member access (IDE0002)". (In a non-generic class, it does.)

